<h1>Online Bible: New World Translation of the Holy Scriptures</h1>
</noscript>
<p class="title">1 Samuel 17:1-58</p>
<form class="formtext">
<input type="hidden" name="chapterCount" value="31">
<input type="hidden" name="verseCount" value="58">
<p><a name="bk1" class="vsAnchor">1</a>
       <span id="vs1">And the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tines went collecting their camps together for war. When they were collected together at So&acute;coh, which belongs to Judah, then they took up camping between So&acute;coh and A&middot;ze&acute;kah, in E&acute;phes-dam&acute;mim.</span> <a name="bk2" class="vsAnchor">2</a>
       <span id="vs2">As for Saul and the men of Israel, they collected themselves together and took up camping in the low plain of E&acute;lah, and they went drawing up in battle formation to meet the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tines.</span> <a name="bk3" class="vsAnchor">3</a>
       <span id="vs3">And the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tines were standing on the mountain on this side, and the Israelites were standing on the mountain on that side, with the valley between them.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk4" class="vsAnchor">4</a>
       <span id="vs4">And a champion began to go out from the camps of the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tines, his name being Go&middot;li&acute;ath, from Gath, his height being six cubits and a span.</span> <a name="bk5" class="vsAnchor">5</a>
       <span id="vs5">And there was a helmet of copper on his head, and he was clad with a coat of mail, of overlapping scales, and the weight of the coat of mail was five thousand shekels of copper.</span> <a name="bk6" class="vsAnchor">6</a>
       <span id="vs6">And there were greaves of copper above his feet and a javelin of copper between his shoulders.</span> <a name="bk7" class="vsAnchor">7</a>
       <span id="vs7">And the wooden shaft of his spear was like the beam of loom workers, and the blade of his spear was six hundred shekels of iron; and the bearer of the large shield was marching ahead of him.</span> <a name="bk8" class="vsAnchor">8</a>
       <span id="vs8">Then he stood still and began to call to the battle lines of Israel and say to them: “Why do <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span> come out to draw up in battle formation? Am I not the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tine and <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span> servants belonging to Saul? Choose a man for yourselves, and let him come down to me.</span> <a name="bk9" class="vsAnchor">9</a>
       <span id="vs9">If he is able to fight with me and he does strike me down, we must then become servants to <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span>. But if I myself am a match for him and I do strike him down, <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span> must also become servants to us, and <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span> must serve us.”</span> <a name="bk10" class="vsAnchor">10</a>
       <span id="vs10">And the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tine went on to say: “I myself do taunt the battle lines of Israel this day. Give me a man, and let us fight together!”</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk11" class="vsAnchor">11</a>
       <span id="vs11">When Saul and all Israel heard these words of the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tine, then they became terrified and were greatly afraid.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk12" class="vsAnchor">12</a>
       <span id="vs12">Now David was the son of this Eph&acute;rath&middot;ite from Beth&acute;le&middot;hem of Judah whose name was Jes&acute;se. And he had eight sons. And in the days of Saul the man was already old among men.</span> <a name="bk13" class="vsAnchor">13</a>
       <span id="vs13">And the three oldest sons of Jes&acute;se proceeded to go. They went after Saul to the war, and the names of his three sons that went into the war were E&middot;li&acute;ab the firstborn, and his second son A&middot;bin&acute;a&middot;dab and the third Sham&acute;mah.</span> <a name="bk14" class="vsAnchor">14</a>
       <span id="vs14">And David was the youngest, and the three oldest themselves went after Saul.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk15" class="vsAnchor">15</a>
       <span id="vs15">And David was going and returning from Saul to tend the sheep of his father at Beth&acute;le&middot;hem.</span> <a name="bk16" class="vsAnchor">16</a>
       <span id="vs16">And the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tine kept coming forward at early morning and at evening and taking his position for forty days.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk17" class="vsAnchor">17</a>
       <span id="vs17">Then Jes&acute;se said to David his son: “Take, please, to your brothers this e&acute;phah of roasted grain and these ten loaves of bread, and carry them quickly to the camp to your brothers.</span> <a name="bk18" class="vsAnchor">18</a>
       <span id="vs18">And these ten portions of milk you should bring to the chief of the thousand; also, you should look after your own brothers as regards their welfare, and a token from them you should take.”</span> <a name="bk19" class="vsAnchor">19</a>
       <span id="vs19">Meantime, Saul and they and all the other men of Israel were in the low plain of E&acute;lah, fighting against the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tines.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk20" class="vsAnchor">20</a>
       <span id="vs20">Accordingly David got up early in the morning and left the sheep to the keeper’s charge and picked up and went just as Jes&acute;se had commanded him. When he came to the camp enclosure, the military forces were going out to the battle line, and they raised a shout for the battle.</span> <a name="bk21" class="vsAnchor">21</a>
       <span id="vs21">And Israel and the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tines began drawing up battle line to meet battle line.</span> <a name="bk22" class="vsAnchor">22</a>
       <span id="vs22">Immediately David left the baggage from off him to the care of the keeper of the baggage and went running to the battle line. When he came, he began asking about the welfare of his brothers.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk23" class="vsAnchor">23</a>
       <span id="vs23">While he was speaking with them, why, here the champion, his name being Go&middot;li&acute;ath the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tine from Gath, was coming up from the battle lines of the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tines, and he began speaking the same words as before, and David got to listen in.</span> <a name="bk24" class="vsAnchor">24</a>
       <span id="vs24">As for all the men of Israel, on their seeing the man, why, they went fleeing on account of him and were very much afraid.</span> <a name="bk25" class="vsAnchor">25</a>
       <span id="vs25">And the men of Israel began to say: “Have <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span> seen this man that is coming up? For it is to taunt Israel that he is coming up. And it must occur that, the man who strikes him down, the king will enrich him with great riches, and his own daughter he will give him, and the house of his father he will set free in Israel.”</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk26" class="vsAnchor">26</a>
       <span id="vs26">And David began to say to the men that were standing close by him: “What will be done to the man that strikes down that Phi&middot;lis&acute;tine over there and actually turns away reproach from upon Israel? For who is this uncircumcised Phi&middot;lis&acute;tine that he has to taunt the battle lines of the living God?”</span> <a name="bk27" class="vsAnchor">27</a>
       <span id="vs27">Then the people said to him the same words as before, saying: “This is the way it will be done to the man that strikes him down.”</span> <a name="bk28" class="vsAnchor">28</a>
       <span id="vs28">And E&middot;li&acute;ab his oldest brother got to hear as he spoke to the men, and E&middot;li&acute;ab’s anger grew hot against David, so that he said: “Why is it that you have come down? And in whose charge did you leave those few sheep behind in the wilderness? I myself well know your presumptuousness and the badness of your heart, because you have come down for the purpose of seeing the battle.”</span> <a name="bk29" class="vsAnchor">29</a>
       <span id="vs29">To this David said: “What have I done now? Was it not just a word?”</span> <a name="bk30" class="vsAnchor">30</a>
       <span id="vs30">With that he turned about from beside him toward someone else and went saying the same word as before, and, in turn, the people gave him the same reply as formerly.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk31" class="vsAnchor">31</a>
       <span id="vs31">So the words that David spoke came to be heard, and they went telling them before Saul. Hence he fetched him.</span> <a name="bk32" class="vsAnchor">32</a>
       <span id="vs32">And David proceeded to say to Saul: “Do not let the heart of any man collapse within him. Your servant himself will go and actually fight with this Phi&middot;lis&acute;tine.”</span> <a name="bk33" class="vsAnchor">33</a>
       <span id="vs33">But Saul said to David: “You are not able to go against this Phi&middot;lis&acute;tine to fight with him, for you are but a boy, and he is a man of war from his boyhood.”</span> <a name="bk34" class="vsAnchor">34</a>
       <span id="vs34">And David went on to say to Saul: “Your servant became a shepherd of his father among the flock, and there came a lion, and also a bear, and [each] carried off a sheep from the drove.</span> <a name="bk35" class="vsAnchor">35</a>
       <span id="vs35">And I went out after it and struck it down and made the rescue from its mouth. When it began rising against me, I grabbed hold of its beard and struck it down and put it to death.</span> <a name="bk36" class="vsAnchor">36</a>
       <span id="vs36">Both the lion and the bear your servant struck down; and this uncircumcised Phi&middot;lis&acute;tine must become like one of them, for he has taunted the battle lines of the living God.”</span> <a name="bk37" class="vsAnchor">37</a>
       <span id="vs37">Then David added: “Jehovah, who delivered me from the paw of the lion and from the paw of the bear, he it is who will deliver me from the hand of this Phi&middot;lis&acute;tine.” At this Saul said to David: “Go, and may Jehovah himself prove to be with you.”</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk38" class="vsAnchor">38</a>
       <span id="vs38">Saul now went clothing David with his garments, and he put a copper helmet upon his head, after which he clothed him with a coat of mail.</span> <a name="bk39" class="vsAnchor">39</a>
       <span id="vs39">Then David girded his sword on over his garments and undertook to go [but could not], because he had not tried them out. Finally David said to Saul: “I am unable to go in these things, for I have not tried them out.” So David removed them off him.</span> <a name="bk40" class="vsAnchor">40</a>
       <span id="vs40">And he proceeded to take his staff in his hand and to choose for himself the five smoothest stones from the torrent valley and to place them in his shepherds’ bag that served him as a receptacle, and in his hand was his sling. And he began approaching the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tine.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk41" class="vsAnchor">41</a>
       <span id="vs41">And the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tine began to come, coming nearer and nearer to David, and the man carrying the large shield was ahead of him.</span> <a name="bk42" class="vsAnchor">42</a>
       <span id="vs42">Now when the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tine looked and saw David, he began despising him because he proved to be a boy and ruddy, of beautiful appearance.</span> <a name="bk43" class="vsAnchor">43</a>
       <span id="vs43">So the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tine said to David: “Am I a dog, so that you are coming to me with staves?” With that the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tine called down evil upon David by his gods.</span> <a name="bk44" class="vsAnchor">44</a>
       <span id="vs44">And the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tine went on to say to David: “Just come to me, and I will give your flesh to the fowls of the heavens and to the beasts of the field.”</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk45" class="vsAnchor">45</a>
       <span id="vs45">In turn David said to the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tine: “You are coming to me with a sword and with a spear and with a javelin, but I am coming to you with the name of Jehovah of armies, the God of the battle lines of Israel, whom you have taunted.</span> <a name="bk46" class="vsAnchor">46</a>
       <span id="vs46">This day Jehovah will surrender you into my hand, and I shall certainly strike you down and remove your head off you; and I shall certainly give the carcasses of the camp of the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tines this day to the fowls of the heavens and to the wild beasts of the earth; and people of all the earth will know that there exists a God belonging to Israel.</span> <a name="bk47" class="vsAnchor">47</a>
       <span id="vs47">And all this congregation will know that neither with sword nor with spear does Jehovah save, because to Jehovah belongs the battle, and he must give <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span> men into our hand.”</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk48" class="vsAnchor">48</a>
       <span id="vs48">And it occurred that the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tine rose and kept coming and drawing nearer to meet David, and David began hurrying and running toward the battle line to meet the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tine.</span> <a name="bk49" class="vsAnchor">49</a>
       <span id="vs49">Then David thrust his hand into his bag and took a stone from there and slung it, so that he struck the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tine in his forehead and the stone sank into his forehead, and he went falling upon his face to the earth.</span> <a name="bk50" class="vsAnchor">50</a>
       <span id="vs50">So David, with a sling and a stone, proved stronger than the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tine and struck the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tine down and put him to death; and there was no sword in David’s hand.</span> <a name="bk51" class="vsAnchor">51</a>
       <span id="vs51">And David continued running and got to stand over the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tine. Then he took his sword and pulled it out of its sheath and definitely put him to death when he cut his head off with it. And the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tines got to see that their mighty one had died, and they took to flight.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk52" class="vsAnchor">52</a>
       <span id="vs52">At that the men of Israel and of Judah rose and broke into shouting and went in pursuit of the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tines clear to [the] valley and as far as the gates of Ek&acute;ron, and the fatally wounded of the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tines kept falling on the way from Sha&acute;a&middot;ra&acute;im, both as far as Gath and as far as Ek&acute;ron.</span> <a name="bk53" class="vsAnchor">53</a>
       <span id="vs53">Afterward the sons of Israel returned from hotly pursuing the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tines and went pillaging their camps.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk54" class="vsAnchor">54</a>
       <span id="vs54">Then David took the head of the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tine and brought it to Jerusalem, and his weapons he put in his tent.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk55" class="vsAnchor">55</a>
       <span id="vs55">Now at the moment that Saul saw David going out to meet the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tine, he said to Ab&acute;ner the chief of the army: “Whose son is the boy, Ab&acute;ner?” To this Ab&acute;ner said: “By the life of your soul, O king, I do not know at all!”</span> <a name="bk56" class="vsAnchor">56</a>
       <span id="vs56">So the king said: “You inquire whose son the lad is.”</span> <a name="bk57" class="vsAnchor">57</a>
       <span id="vs57">Accordingly, as soon as David returned from striking the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tine down, Ab&acute;ner proceeded to take him and bring him before Saul with the head of the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tine in his hand.</span> <a name="bk58" class="vsAnchor">58</a>
       <span id="vs58">Saul now said to him: “Whose son are you, boy?” to which David said: “The son of your servant Jes&acute;se the Beth&acute;le&middot;hem&middot;ite.”</span>
</p>
</form>

