<h1>Online Bible: New World Translation of the Holy Scriptures</h1>
</noscript>
<p class="title">1 Samuel 23:1-29</p>
<form class="formtext">
<input type="hidden" name="chapterCount" value="31">
<input type="hidden" name="verseCount" value="29">
<p><a name="bk1" class="vsAnchor">1</a>
       <span id="vs1">In time they came reporting to David, saying: “Here the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tines are warring against Kei&acute;lah, and they are pillaging the threshing floors.”</span> <a name="bk2" class="vsAnchor">2</a>
       <span id="vs2">And David proceeded to inquire of Jehovah, saying: “Shall I go, and must I strike down these Phi&middot;lis&acute;tines?” In turn Jehovah said to David: “Go, and you must strike down the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tines and save Kei&acute;lah.”</span> <a name="bk3" class="vsAnchor">3</a>
       <span id="vs3">At this the men of David said to him: “Look! We are afraid while here in Judah, and how much more so in case we should go to Kei&acute;lah against the battle lines of the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tines!”</span> <a name="bk4" class="vsAnchor">4</a>
       <span id="vs4">So David inquired yet again of Jehovah. Jehovah now answered him and said: “Rise up, go down to Kei&acute;lah, because I am giving the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tines into your hand.”</span> <a name="bk5" class="vsAnchor">5</a>
       <span id="vs5">Accordingly David went with his men to Kei&acute;lah and fought against the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tines and drove off with their livestock, but struck them down with a great slaughter; and David came to be the savior of the inhabitants of Kei&acute;lah.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk6" class="vsAnchor">6</a>
       <span id="vs6">Now it came about that when A&middot;bi&acute;a&middot;thar the son of A&middot;him&acute;e&middot;lech ran away to David at Kei&acute;lah, there was an eph&acute;od that went down in his hand.</span> <a name="bk7" class="vsAnchor">7</a>
       <span id="vs7">In time the report was made to Saul: “David has come to Kei&acute;lah.” And Saul began to say: “God has sold him into my hand, for he has shut himself up by coming into a city with doors and bar.”</span> <a name="bk8" class="vsAnchor">8</a>
       <span id="vs8">So Saul summoned all the people to war, to go down to Kei&acute;lah, to besiege David and his men.</span> <a name="bk9" class="vsAnchor">9</a>
       <span id="vs9">And David got to know that Saul was fabricating mischief against him. Hence he said to A&middot;bi&acute;a&middot;thar the priest: “Do bring the eph&acute;od near.”</span> <a name="bk10" class="vsAnchor">10</a>
       <span id="vs10">And David went on to say: “O Jehovah the God of Israel, your servant has definitely heard that Saul is seeking to come to Kei&acute;lah to lay the city in ruin on my account.</span> <a name="bk11" class="vsAnchor">11</a>
       <span id="vs11">Will the landowners of Kei&acute;lah surrender me into his hand? Will Saul come down just as your servant has heard? O Jehovah the God of Israel, tell your servant, please.” To this Jehovah said: “He will come down.”</span> <a name="bk12" class="vsAnchor">12</a>
       <span id="vs12">And David went on to say: “Will the landowners of Kei&acute;lah surrender me and my men into Saul’s hand?” In turn Jehovah said: “They will do the surrendering.”</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk13" class="vsAnchor">13</a>
       <span id="vs13">At once David rose up with his men, about six hundred men, and they went out of Kei&acute;lah and continued walking about wherever they could walk about. And to Saul it was reported that David had escaped from Kei&acute;lah, and so he gave up going out.</span> <a name="bk14" class="vsAnchor">14</a>
       <span id="vs14">And David took up dwelling in the wilderness in places difficult to approach, and he kept dwelling in the mountainous region in the wilderness of Ziph. And Saul kept looking for him always, and God did not give him into his hand.</span> <a name="bk15" class="vsAnchor">15</a>
       <span id="vs15">And David continued in fear because Saul had gone out to look for his soul while David was in the wilderness of Ziph at Ho&acute;resh.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk16" class="vsAnchor">16</a>
       <span id="vs16">Jon&acute;a&middot;than the son of Saul now rose up and went to David at Ho&acute;resh, that he might strengthen his hand in regard to God.</span> <a name="bk17" class="vsAnchor">17</a>
       <span id="vs17">And he went on to say to him: “Do not be afraid; for the hand of Saul my father will not find you, and you yourself will be king over Israel, and I myself shall become second to you; and Saul my father also has knowledge to that effect.”</span> <a name="bk18" class="vsAnchor">18</a>
       <span id="vs18">Then the two of them concluded a covenant before Jehovah; and David kept dwelling in Ho&acute;resh, and Jon&acute;a&middot;than himself went to his own home.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk19" class="vsAnchor">19</a>
       <span id="vs19">Later the men of Ziph went up to Saul at Gib&acute;e&middot;ah, saying: “Is not David concealing himself close by us in the places difficult to approach at Ho&acute;resh, on the hill of Hach&middot;i&acute;lah, which is to the right side of Je&middot;shi&acute;mon?</span> <a name="bk20" class="vsAnchor">20</a>
       <span id="vs20">And now in harmony with all the craving of your soul, O king, to come down, come down, and our part will be to surrender him into the hand of the king.”</span> <a name="bk21" class="vsAnchor">21</a>
       <span id="vs21">At this Saul said: “Blessed are <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span> of Jehovah, for <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span> have had compassion on me.</span> <a name="bk22" class="vsAnchor">22</a>
       <span id="vs22">Go, please, persevere some more and ascertain and see his place where his foot comes to be—whoever saw him there—for it has been said to me that he himself is surely cunning.</span> <a name="bk23" class="vsAnchor">23</a>
       <span id="vs23">And see and ascertain about all the hiding places where he hides himself; and <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span> must return to me with the evidence, and I will go with <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span>; and it must occur that, if he is in the land, I will also search for him carefully among all the thousands of Judah.”</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk24" class="vsAnchor">24</a>
       <span id="vs24">So they rose up and went to Ziph ahead of Saul, while David and his men were in the wilderness of Ma&acute;on in the Ar&acute;a&middot;bah to the south of Je&middot;shi&acute;mon.</span> <a name="bk25" class="vsAnchor">25</a>
       <span id="vs25">Later Saul came with his men to look for him. When they told David, he at once went down to the crag and continued dwelling in the wilderness of Ma&acute;on. When Saul got to hear of it, he went chasing after David into the wilderness of Ma&acute;on.</span> <a name="bk26" class="vsAnchor">26</a>
       <span id="vs26">Eventually Saul came to this side of the mountain, and David and his men were on that side of the mountain. So David became hurried to go away because of Saul; all the while Saul and his men were closing in on David and his men to grab hold of them.</span> <a name="bk27" class="vsAnchor">27</a>
       <span id="vs27">But there was a messenger that came to Saul, saying: “Do hasten and go, for the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tines have made a raid on the land!”</span> <a name="bk28" class="vsAnchor">28</a>
       <span id="vs28">At that Saul turned back from chasing after David and went to meet the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tines. That is why they have called that place the Crag of the Divisions.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk29" class="vsAnchor">29</a>
       <span id="vs29">Then David made his way up from there and took up dwelling in the places difficult to approach at En-ge&acute;di.</span>
</p>
</form>

